  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An international organization that sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime - Provides guidelines for countries to combat money laundering\n\n3. The Palermo Convention - Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee Recommendations - Sets banking standards to prevent financial crimes\n\n5. The Egmont Group - An international network of financial intelligence units that share information\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\nThese laws generally require banks and financial institutions to monitor and report potential money laundering activities to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds.",
